      </div>
      <div class="section-heading"><span class="sh-icon">📝</span>Core Concepts Explained</div>
      <div class="explanation-box">
        <div class="box-label">12 IMPORTANT ACCOUNTING CONCEPTS</div>
        <p>
          <strong>1. Entity Concept:</strong> Business aur Owner alag hain — Business ke accounts mein sirf business ke transactions aate hain.<br><br>
          <strong>2. Going Concern Concept:</strong> Assume karo ki Business indefinitely chalti rahegi — isliye assets ko cost pe dikhate hain, not liquidation value.<br><br>
          <strong>3. Money Measurement Concept:</strong> Sirf woh cheezein accounts mein record hoti hain jo paise mein measure ho sakti hain (Employee loyalty → record nahi hogi).<br><br>
          <strong>4. Cost Concept / Historical Cost:</strong> Assets ko unki original cost pe record karo, market value pe nahi.<br><br>
          <strong>5. Dual Aspect Concept:</strong> Har transaction ke do effects hote hain → <span style="color:#1565c0;font-weight:700;">Assets = Liabilities + Capital</span> (Golden Rule)<br><br>
          <strong>6. Realization Concept:</strong> Revenue tab record karo jab earn ho — cash mile ya na mile (Credit sales bhi income hai).<br><br>
          <strong>7. Accrual Concept:</strong> Revenue aur Expenses ko related period mein record karo, cash movement pe nahi.<br><br>
          <strong>8. Matching Concept:</strong> Revenue ke saath related expenses match karo → Tab hi sahi profit pata chalega.<br><br>
          <strong>9. Consistency Concept:</strong> Ek baar ek method choose karo aur baar baar use karo — comparison easy hoti hai.<br><br>
          <strong>10. Conservatism / Prudence:</strong> "Anticipate no profit, but provide for all possible losses" — Sadguni businessman ki tarah sochna.<br><br>
          <strong>11. Materiality Concept:</strong> Small/insignificant items ke liye strict rules follow karna zaruri nahi.<br><br>
          <strong>12. Full Disclosure:</strong> Accounts mein saari important information clearly dikhao.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="formula-box">
        <div class="formula-title">📐 Capital vs Revenue — Quick Difference</div>
        <span class="highlight">Capital Expenditure</span> = Benefit > 1 Year | Asset Create Hota Hai | Balance Sheet pe<br>
        Examples: Purchase of Machine, Building Construction, Legal fees for property<br><br>
        <span class="gold">Revenue Expenditure</span> = Benefit ≤ 1 Year | P&amp;L Account pe<br>
        Examples: Salaries, Rent, Repairs to Machine, Purchase of Goods<br><br>
        <span class="highlight">Capital Receipt</span> = Non-recurring | Capital Fund se (Loan, Sale of Asset)<br>
        <span class="gold">Revenue Receipt</span> = Recurring | Operations se (Sales, Commission received)
      </div>
      <div class="section-heading"><span class="sh-icon">❓</span>Sample Questions &amp; Solutions</div>
      <div class="question-card">
        <div class="question-header" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
          <span class="q-badge">Q.1</span>
          <p>Explain the Matching Concept. A company incurs advertising expense of ₹1,20,000 in March 2025 for a campaign that will benefit April-June 2025. How should this be treated?</p>
          <span class="qtoggle">▼</span>
        </div>
        <div class="question-solution">
          <p><strong>Matching Concept:</strong> Expenses ko us accounting period mein record karo jis period mein unse related revenue earn kiya gaya ho — chahe cash payment kab bhi hua ho.</p>
          <p style="margin-top:12px;"><strong>Treatment of Advertising Expense:</strong></p>
          <div class="sol-step"><div class="step-num">1</div><p>₹1,20,000 expense March 2025 mein hua lekin benefit April-June 2025 mein milega</p></div>
          <div class="sol-step"><div class="step-num">2</div><p>March 2025 ke accounts mein ₹0 show hoga (no related revenue in March)</p></div>
          <div class="sol-step"><div class="step-num">3</div><p>₹1,20,000 ko "Prepaid Advertising" (Asset) ki tarah Balance Sheet mein dikhao March 2025 mein</p></div>
          <div class="sol-step"><div class="step-num">4</div><p>April-June 2025 mein ₹40,000/month P&L mein expense karo (₹1,20,000 ÷ 3 months)</p></div>
          <p style="margin-top:10px;background:#e8f5e9;padding:10px;border-radius:8px;font-size:13px;"><strong>Result:</strong> Matching Concept ensure karta hai ki correct profit calculate ho — right period mein right expense.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="question-card">
        <div class="question-header" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
          <span class="q-badge">Q.2</span>
          <p>Classify the following as Capital or Revenue Expenditure: (a) ₹50,000 spent on whitewashing factory (b) ₹2,00,000 spent on extension of factory building (c) ₹5,000 spent on carriage for new machine (d) ₹15,000 spent on annual maintenance of machine</p>
          <span class="qtoggle">▼</span>
        </div>
        <div class="question-solution">
          <table class="table-simple">
            <tr><th>Item</th><th>Classification</th><th>Reason</th></tr>
            <tr><td>(a) Whitewashing ₹50,000</td><td>Revenue Expenditure</td><td>Recurring, no new asset, P&L mein jata hai</td></tr>
            <tr><td>(b) Factory Extension ₹2,00,000</td><td>Capital Expenditure</td><td>Existing building ka value badhaya, Balance Sheet mein</td></tr>
            <tr><td>(c) Carriage for Machine ₹5,000</td><td>Capital Expenditure</td><td>Machine ki cost ka hissa — machine ke value mein add karo</td></tr>
            <tr><td>(d) Annual Maintenance ₹15,000</td><td>Revenue Expenditure</td><td>Regular maintenance, recurring, P&L mein debit</td></tr>
          </table>
        </div>
